Concept: Socket Address & Port Numbers

A socket address uniquely identifies one endpoint of communication by combining an IP address and a port number.

Example:

192.168.1.15:443

A port number identifies which application or service should receive the incoming data.

Examples:

HTTP → 80
HTTPS → 443
SSH → 22
DNS → 53
SMTP → 25

Without ports, the operating system wouldn't know whether incoming data belongs to Chrome, Discord, SSH, or another application.

Cybersecurity Relevance

Ports are the primary entry points attackers investigate during reconnaissance. Every exposed service listening on a port represents a potential attack surface.

Malware also opens sockets to establish reverse shells or communicate with Command-and-Control (C2) servers.

Tools
Nmap – Scan hosts for open TCP/UDP ports.
Netcat (nc) – Create TCP/UDP connections, bind shells, and reverse shells.
ss / netstat – View active sockets and listening services.
Wireshark – Inspect traffic to and from specific ports.
Blue Team (Defenders)

Process: Monitor listening ports, disable unnecessary services, detect unexpected outbound connections, and enforce firewall rules to restrict access to sensitive services.

End Goal: Reduce the attack surface and quickly identify unauthorized network services or malware communications.

Red Team (Attackers)

Process: Perform port scanning to identify exposed services, determine software versions, and locate vulnerable applications for exploitation.

End Goal: Discover an entry point into the target network.
